Author-Name:    Sproul, Michael F
Title:   Antitrust and Prices. 
Journal: Journal of Political Economy
Pages: 741-54
Issue: 4
Volume: 101
Year: 1993
Month:  August 
Abstract:
  This study examines the effects of antitrust prosecution on prices
 charged by firms indicted for price fixing. In a survey of twenty-five
 cases filed between 1973 and 1984, prices are found to gradually rise by
 about 7 percent over the four years following an indictment. However, the
 severity of penalties is negatively correlated with prices. These two
 findings suggest either that penalties are too lenient or that prosecution
 is too broad, penalizing economically efficient conspiracies along with
 those that are inefficient.  Copyright 1993 by University of Chicago Press.
